key; its only limit is MySQL's row-format/charset-dependent index key-length limit, which the neutral model cannot know and which the server enforces at execution (a loud error, not silent churn) â€” verified that TINYTEXT `col(255)` AND `col(256)` both error \"max key length 255 bytes\".\n\nDesign decisions (maintainer-confirmed): (1) prefix on the shared Constraint covering PK+unique; (2) reject non-string / full-width prefixes; (3) column-aware validation lives in the backend (generalizes to other backends); (4) stop validation at the statically-sound rules â€” the index key-length limit is un-static-validatable.\n\nLocal codex 8 rounds (most valid hardening: prefix-order churn across canonicalize/offline-diff/direct-diff, preflight shape + column-aware validation, backend-owned architecture, Raw string/binary recognition; dismissed a false positive re: constraint-name = index-name; R7â†”R8 flip-flopped on LOB capacity â†’ resolved by verifying the real limit is runtime). Verified: fmt, workspace clippy `-D warnings`, full `--all-features` tests, compile_fail; live MySQL round-trip publishes VARCHAR + PK + VARBINARY prefixes and re-plans empty.","files":null}]}